# Security Review

## Input Validation
- Validate and sanitize ALL user input at the boundary (API handlers, form processors)
- Use allowlists over denylists for input validation
- Validate data types, lengths, ranges, and formats
- Never trust client-side validation alone — always validate server-side

## Authentication & Authorization
- Use established auth libraries (passport, next-auth, django-auth) — don't roll your own
- Hash passwords with bcrypt/argon2 — never MD5/SHA for passwords
- Implement rate limiting on auth endpoints
- Check authorization on every request, not just at the route level
- Use short-lived tokens (JWTs: <15 min) with refresh token rotation

## Injection Prevention
- Use parameterized queries / ORM methods — never string-concatenate SQL
- Escape output for the context (HTML, URL, JS, CSS)
- Use Content Security Policy headers
- Validate file uploads: check MIME type, limit size, rename files

## Secrets
- NEVER hardcode secrets, API keys, or passwords in source code
- Use environment variables or a secrets manager (Vault, AWS Secrets Manager)
- Add secret patterns to `.gitignore` and use git-secrets or gitleaks
- Rotate credentials regularly and after any suspected exposure

## Data Protection
- Encrypt sensitive data at rest and in transit (TLS everywhere)
- Minimize data collection — don't store what you don't need
- Log security events but NEVER log sensitive data (passwords, tokens, PII)
- Implement proper error handling that doesn't leak internal details
